ls : list files
ls -a : list hidden files too
ls -l : lists all contents of a directory in long format
ls -t : order files and directories by the time they were last modified.
ls -alt : list everything everything 
pwd : print working directory
cd : change directory
cd : To move up one directory,
mkdir : making directory
touch : creation of the world
mv filename directory : moves file
cp filename directoery : copy files
rm : removbes files
rm -r : recursiv silir all chiled directories too
rm director/* : deletess all files indirector
echo "Hello" > hello.txt : creation
cat hello.txt : read file
cat glaciers.txt > rivers.txt  : outputs only glaciers
cat glaciers.txt >> rivers.txt : output botth
sort file.txt : elifba sirasina gore duzur icini
uniq : similarlari silir
grep Mount mountains.txt : grep stands for “global regular expression print”. It searches files for lines that match a pattern and returns the results. It is also case sensitive. Here, grep searches for “Mount” in mountains.tx
grep -i Mount mountains.txt : grep -i enables the command to be case insensitive. Here, grep searches for capital or lowercase strings that match Mount in mountains.txt.
sed 's/snow/rain/' forests.txt : sed stands for “stream editor”. It accepts standard input and modifies it based on an expression, before displaying it as output data. It is similar to “find and replace”.
/*
Let’s look at the expression 's/snow/rain/':

s: stands for “substitution”. it is always used when using sed for substitution.
snow: the search string, the text to find.
rain: the replacement string, the text to add in place.
*/
